Parliament has not ratified the amendment for the release of Tymoshenko
The Ukrainian parliament has rejected, as part of an amendment to criminal law, the draft cancellation of the paragraph on the indictment of Yulia Tymoshenko, the head of the opposition.
The deputies rejected at second reading the draft amendment aimed at the reduction of sentences for economic crimes, which could have opened the doors of freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymoshenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for having concluded an a priori disadvantageous agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not final and the court must decide on the appeal of the convicted woman in December.
Tymoshenko calls the regime’s political vendetta judgment and has provoked a process of suspicions of court bias also in the west.
The draft to repeal paragraph 365 of the criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 MPs.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
