Feeding an obese child: does not take breakfast and takes charcuterie for dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have overweight problems, 9% of schoolchildren are overweight and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families that have an unhealthy lifestyle.
This again shows how important the environment in which the human being evolves and the models that surround him.
On the tables of obese children, for example, charcuterie is found 50% more often than in families of children with normal weight.
19% of obese women had french fries at dinner, according to the survey conducted with an awareness action "Obesity is not a coincidence"
In the families of the big kids sport is also not a habit, which is now the case for most schoolchildren today - only 15% replied that at least once a week parents found time for active movement.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place during the last school year and involved 900 pupils from primary schools in the Czech Republic.
This was the second edition of "Obesity is not a coincidence", an action supported by the General Health Insurance and Unilever.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 students from sixth to third have signed up for this project.
One of the determining factors that cause a dramatic increase in the number of overweight or even obese children is the lack of proper nutrition and not enough physical exercise.
“Only half of the children surveyed indicated, for example, eating breakfast 5 times a day – in the case of lunch – snack – dinner, which is one of the basic principles of good nutrition,” says one of the survey results.
Without breakfast and charcuterie at dinner
Specialists draw attention to the fact that to have a healthy development you need some basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of students’ families eat at the same time.
In most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
And the worst that has been noted is that one-tenth of the population does not eat breakfast at all.
However, breakfast is the basis of a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that families of obese children consume unhealthy fries more often.
Almost every student - not to mention the weight - drinks sugary drinks (70%) every day.
More than 40% of children surveyed do sports regularly but for parents it is half, only 15%.
Prepare your food.
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own food based on the possibilities offered according to their own taste and personal opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 years are far from ideal, in terms of a healthy diet."
Among their favorite dishes there are a lot of cakes, meats and sweets.
"The most alarming is a high preference for sweet lemonades," the survey found.
For lunch it is the pasta that took the first place right in front of the white meat.
The children did not want starches at all and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Heading towards health
The survey also showed that children are ready to change their habits from the moment they receive the ad hoc information.
"During a group of survey participants who had completed the questionnaire after the 'Obesity is not a coincidence' awareness session, there was a strong will to move towards healthy eating," the survey results say.
The most striking was, for example, with regard to sweet lemonades as children began to give preference to drinking water.
The children most often checked on the questionnaire white meat and fish as the main dish and would reduce sweet dishes and "knedliky" (Czech speciality of bread flour balls or potatoes).
