History of IBM: From slices of cheese to flights into the cosmos.
IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York a hundred years ago; it was originally called the Computation Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It took the name IBM in 1924 - initially it was a brand used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The basis of the future IBM was the merger of four firms whose history is related to the 80's of the nineteenth century.
They possessed technologies such as the old "pointers", the pendulums that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint who until 1930 chaired the Supervisory Board of the company.
Flint hired the head of a rival firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The leader then cast a shadow over the firm's founder - it was Watson's ideas that have so far shaped the company's identity and culture.
Watson ran the firm until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, started with the production of all possible machines for business and commerce – from cheese and meat slicers to cash registers.
In the first four years of Watson's leadership, sales increased to $9 million and the firm began expanding to all parts of the world.
Watson was so irreplaceable for the firm that after 40 years of management, it was his son who occupied the director's chair, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM’s people and computers helped NASA guide flights into the cosmos—on Mercury, Saturn, and in 1969, the flight to the Moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first family of computers, the IBM System/360.
The classic PC that determined the computer standard of the time with the name IBM 5150 came on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer factory to the Chinese company Lenovo, but bought the consulting firm Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to take care of consulting and services with high added value.
The strategy that has been successful at IBM for the past three years - is the Smarter Planet concept "a smarter planet".
Its objective is the intelligent use of technology in areas not yet exploited, such as transport and urban management.
In terms of commerce, IBM recently developed a “Smarter Commerce” platform that helps marketers manage the entire business cycle.
IBM has a strong history in our territory as well.
It established its branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932, then the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM RT, there is also the strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Central and Eastern Europe Centre is based in Prague and there is also the world-class research and development team that is responsible for speech recognition.
