Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He wrote here an extraordinary book which he describes, with exactitude, as "a work of anti-history."
It contains some well-known names, important treaties or famous battles; there is almost no ambassador or discussion of strategies and equipment.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as a "book describing what it might look like." It contains "feelings, impressions, experiences, and moods."
“Beauty and Grief” summarizes the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women, from both sides of the war, from young schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, to doctors, ambulances and salesmen.
Some of them will become heroes.
Other prisoners of war, some of whom will lose members, go mad, or lose their lives.
Their lives waver here like the candles of a church: while some are extinguished, new ones are rekindled.
Peter Englund’s book departs from traditional history books.
He denies the idea that the First World War can only be summed up by the terrible war of trenches on the Western front.
"Beauty and Grief" skillfully describes other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers present in this book are under hives; one Christmas pass in Egypt under the pyramids; the tsetse flies are an intractable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
War invades the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like a Katrina hurricane that stinks of cordite.
When cannon shots are heard in the distance, and you are a mother at home, do you stay or do you run?
Who will come anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, not even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, "the lack of facts has been stifled by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors."
"Beauty and Grief" follows individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor in the German high seas fleet.
Their stories are mainly taken from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
Versions of their lives can be terrifying or exciting, but are most preserved thanks to the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
Most address deprivation and the ability to get out of it.
In telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, everywhere ersatz."
"Replacement coffee, false aluminum, rubber imitation, paper bandages, wooden buttons."
It continues on alternative food in Germany.
He describes "meat made from cooked rice crushed into sheep fat (and finished with a fake wooden bone); tobacco made with dry roots and dried skin from potatoes; wooden shoe soles."
He states that "837 authorized substitute meats are recorded in the production of sausages. There are also 511 substitute coffees."
Some stories deal with honor and courage.
An American acknowledges his own drive toward savagery and declares about the war: "You feel that after all, this is what men were meant for, rather than sitting in a comfortable chair, a cigarette and a whisky in hand, reading a newspaper or a bestseller, and rather than pretending that such a vernissage is not yours and does not claim to be such a vernissity.
Conversely, a British soldier realizes that he is in great danger of dying, and that no one will notice or pay attention to it.
