This is, unfortunately, rather comparable to “a convicted man strangled in secret.”
Other observations concern the decline of an old Europe and new types of terror.
“The conflict is becoming more and more a story of economic competition,” writes Peter Englund, “a war between factories.”
He captures the arrival of what he calls “a new species within the early-century bestiary: the well-articulated and ideologically convinced mass murderer, in well-cut clothes, who executes his butchery while sitting behind a counter.”
People act in unexpected ways; there are as many basic behaviors as there are heroism.
Peter Englund talks about soldiers who tried at all costs to catch a venereal disease in prostitutes in order to avoid service at the front.
"We find the most grotesque expression in the pus trade due to gonorrhea, which soldiers buy and spread on the genitals in the hope of ending up in the hospital," he wrote.
“The most desperate apply it to the eyes, which translates into lifelong blindness.”
In this translation from Swedish by Peter Graves, Peter Englund's prose is flexible but not ostentatious, perfectly adapted to his task as a human being.
In dozens of short scenes, he captures the way war has “triggered exclusively uncontrollable forces: extreme nationalism, social revolution, aversion to religion.”
People are starting to wonder why their leaders are waging war on them.
The best works dealing with the First World War are often indirect, such as Paul Fussel's "Great War and Modern Memory," or Erich Maria Remarque's "To the West Nothing New," rather than complete.
Peter Englund's work is an unconventional pantheon.
The end of the book is the most overwhelming I’ve read in a non-fictional work.
I won't reveal it.
