7 Lessons from Steve Jobs’ Lost Interview at the Movies This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford - distinguished by the technical genius and inventor of modern computing.
But what Apple fans may find most revealing in a recent interview with Steve Jobs that will air this week in the first part of a film on major markets, is how much that creative spirit had understood the processes and workflows of the products.
He was undoubtedly a creator and a dreamer. He identified himself as a hippie but was also very meticulous and organized, as well as an organigram improver - a man who believed that many business leaders suffered from a "disease leaving them to think that a brilliant idea does 90% of the work... [but] a considerable amount of geyser work."
In 1995, Bob Cringley developed the television series "Triumph of the Nerds". This series traces the birth of the computer, and he sits for more than an hour with Steve Jobs for a long and rare conversation.
At that time, it was about 10 years ago that Steve Jobs had to leave Apple. He was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, aimed at a popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of the interview with Cringely is used in Nerds, he states that the main copies disappeared in the transport.
It was only after the death of Steve Jobs that a complete video was found in the director’s garage.
This slightly edited video is the basis for the 68-minute film Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview, which will be released in theaters on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Steve Jobs here seems surprisingly enthusiastic about exposing technological philosophies and his business strategies.
And incredibly attentive.
On four different points during the interview, the answers come a long time after the questions - between 10 and 15 seconds of reflection, during which Steve Jobs clearly weighs his thoughts, in order to provide a precise answer.
There are also moments when Steve Jobs’ perfectionism resurfaces, where he seems eager to hear Cringley’s questions, giving him elbow strokes to speed it up and move on to more important questions or topics.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, we find a strangely prescient aspect on Lost Interview. Steve Jobs evaluates what he considers good or bad in other companies and shares his own vision of the future of computing.
It’s one thing to read the posthumous reviews of Steve Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the man we see here, the anxious dreamer on the eve of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
He explains them and then immediately implements them.
Here’s a quick summary of seven remarkable sequences from Lost Interview:
On how he learned to run a business:
“All these years, I’ve always asked, ‘Why do you do things?’ and the answers are constantly the same: ‘Oh, just because you have to do them.’”
No one knows why, no one thinks deeply about things in a company.
That's what I found out.
Steve Jobs continues to provide details on his efforts to simplify accounting at Apple.
Perplexed as to how costs were recorded - one often starts with a "standard cost" assessed at a glance, then adjusted with a "variation" - he developed an automated factory that guaranteed accurate calculation of commercial costs.
On the opportunity to play a tour of the Pope:
Steve Jobs tells the anecdote of the "Blue Box" he created with Steve Wozniak - a device that was used to hack into telephone networks and make free long-distance calls.
The device has been the subject of many writings before, but Steve Jobs’ euphoria here in his description of the Blue Box as an act of appropriation is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box using a public phone, making a call and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while bypassing as many satellites as possible.
“We wrapped the ball of different things a half-dozen times and you screamed in the public phone and it happened to you a minute later on the public phone next door,” says Jobs, laughing.
“We were young and thanks to this Blue Box, we learned that we could create something ourselves that could control billions of dollars of infrastructure around the world.”
We both didn’t know much, but we knew how to come up with a little thing that could control big things. It was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think Apple would have ever existed without it.
Steve Jobs continues by telling a wonderful story that he and Wozniak have developed: he phoned the Vatican with the Blue Box in the middle of the night posing as Henry Kissinger and asked to speak to the Pope.
While several members of the Catholic hierarchy are summoned in the middle of the night to speak to the American diplomat, the two accomplices go out laughing just before the Pope himself is awakened.
On his love of technology (and Bill Hewlett's approach):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to make a frequency meter, he searches for Bill Hewlett's number in the directory and gives him a phone call.
Shortly after their 20-minute conversation, Steve Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
"It had a remarkable influence on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it formed my definition of a company and the way employees are treated."
Steve Jobs later became one of HP's employees to visit the company's research labs, located in Palo Alto, where he discovered the "first desktop computer ever designed."
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a little cathode ray tube, and I fell in love with it.
The teenager that I was went back to HP and started writing programs for that machine.
On the Improvisation of Innovation:
At several points in the interview, Steve Jobs talks about inventing new products at a glance.
At the beginning of his career, as he sets up to sell some printed circuit boards, a client asks him to assemble a complete computer.
Working only 30 credit days, he had to take care of the assembly as well as the delivery of the finished devices.
Later, at Apple, he remembers the difficulties encountered in developing a computer mouse:
"I remember some big fights... I was yelled at and told that it would take me five years [to make a mouse that would cost $300]. I had enough, I went out and saw a designer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could make for $15 and that turned out to be incredibly reliable.
On the big companies that are blowing up:
Long before he revived Apple, Steve Jobs had anticipated how many industrial leaders would go wrong and lose control of their market share.
"Let's say you work at IBM or Xerox, you make a better copier or a better printer, and then what?"
You have the monopoly of the market, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing can make it evolve, so [it’s these types of people] who end up running businesses and product staff are put away from decision-making.
The product engineering that led to this monopoly position is completely rotten by people who can’t imagine designing a good product versus a bad product – the manual work required.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
It could have made ten times its current size. Xerox would have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They snatched the defeat to victory.
On innovation as an artistic form:
"A huge part of manual work separates a great idea from an exceptional product... as you develop that idea, it changes and grows."
You learn a lot about its subtleties.
There are compromises to be made... Some things you can’t do, electrons can do, glass, robots, factories too.
You have to keep thousands of things in mind (these concepts) by assembling them together.
Finally, decisions are made by personal taste. It is about trying to expose yourself to the best products that men have created, and trying to bring these things to the product that you create.
Picasso once said that good artists copy and great artists steal.
We are always ashamed to steal great ideas.
This is partly what makes Macintosh exceptional. The people who worked on it were musicians, poets, zoologists, historians, who simply turned out to be the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn't for computer science, they would have done extraordinary things in another field.
