How to spot a lie
A look at recent headlines shows how much deception and lies are ubiquitous in everyday life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accusing the other of lying.
Penn State administrators have been charged with perjury for allegedly covering reports that a retired football coach sexually assaulted boys.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was taken by an open microphone claiming to U.S. President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
The lie has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York Congressman and Internet celebrity Anthony Weiner has come across as an idiot by quickly issuing denials contradicted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with violations of campaign finance related to the coverage of an extramarital affair.
And then, none of those who have lived through history will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton unleashed by lying in his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating on the tests of the school and the university are legion.
There have been cases where teachers have given test responses to students in order to get a good look at their performance evaluations.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send the message that lying and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we encounter?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are pious lies.
Another study showed that strangers lie three times in the first 10 minutes of their meeting.
Detecting or spotting lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a game of society similar to, say, charades, where the goal is to shout out: "I've had you", the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the last six decades in prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research on such projects, especially in psychology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lies have been debunked.
The liars look you in the eye.
They don’t blush, blush, or always agitate.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to expose.
A qualified lie detector can uncover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, facial microexpressions, question formation, and response time.
I have spent several years examining scientific results in the vast and ever-evolving body of knowledge about deception, and it is clear that the detection of deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful for navigating our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, negotiating or managing.
Good liars are able to read others well, putting them at ease, managing their own emotions and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more lies "centered on them" while women tell more lies "centered on others" - usually to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people (but that lies tend to be more than lies).
We also know that if you are perceived as a disbeliever, others will feel less guilty of lying to you.
How can you tell if someone is lying?
First of all, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
This is what is called "establishing benchmark data".
This helps to provide a reference point for measuring subsequent changes.
Observe the posture of your subject, the laughter, the voice quality.
You need to know if someone normally stirs their feet constantly so as not to throw unfair accusations when you see them stir their feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for signs of verbal and non-verbal deceptive behavior.
Consider these clues as red flags, not evidence of deception.
Deceptive people can immobilize the top of the body when they try to remember their story, they can point their feet toward the door, lean toward an exit, change posture significantly or present a relief from "post-interview" - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all the difficult questions have passed.
Questioners often falsely state that the interview is over just to try to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Also, pay attention to the vocabulary of your subject.
The famous Scott Peterson skidded off using the past while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Deceptive individuals can also use a distant language: "I have not had sex with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat entirely a difficult question.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "wooden tongue" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to be honest... if I remember well... to my knowledge."
This makes the response perceptual rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing the skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone's chances of avoiding victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
