"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former European Commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not say explicitly that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles were overcome.
The “frame is now well laid out,” he added.
Monti completed the process to form a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than normal, while Italy fought a political and financial crisis that pushed its debt costs to levels impossible to sustain.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain confidence in Italy that had been affected.
