The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by noting that a Monti bankruptcy would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations Monday with political parties, trade unions and employers’ groups, and youth and women’s organizations.
He will finish his meeting tour Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief pause at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi was going to resign, the costs of the Italian debt have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty about the new prime minister's success.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.9 trillion, would be too much for the eurozone’s current financial defenses.
