In the exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament said the band is ready to deliver one of their best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
They have waited more than 20 years, but the group assures that for them it will also be a dream come true to occur in this country.
It is that bassist and founding member Jeff Ament assured, speaking exclusively with Viva, of Brazil, last week.
The group is in the South American wing of their two-decade work celebration tour and on Sunday 20 will make its only stopover in Central America.
That day they will perform at the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 pm, next to the Los Angeles group The X and the Nationals of Las Robertas.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which can be found in La Naci<0xC3><0xB3>n on the Internet.
For its Costa Rican fans, the fact that Pearl Jam will take place in Costa Rica is a dream come true. Are you aware of what your fans are experiencing?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream that has become a reality for us too.
This is our second time in South and Central America and so far it has been great.
I only spent in Costa Rica once on vacation; it's such a beautiful country and I think we can spend a few days there.
So it’s exciting to bring our music there.
I ask you, because there is a kind of devotion to the group, the fans live with intensity in the previous days.
What is your message to your most ardent followers?
Thank you for staying with us all these years.
It took 21 years for us to get to Costa Rica; thank you for having waited so long and we are sorry that so much time has had to pass until this concert.
Some people already say that his concert is the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a bit of pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve offered over the last 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We offered a couple of giant shows in Sao Paolo and we hope that it got us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to producing it.
We love this country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its waves to surf?
We have a lot of surfing friends and I have a very good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are amazing there.
My friends were always going to surf in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, next to Mexico, are great places to surf; that’s how we learned, through the people who love surfing.
Seeing the tour, you have offered huge shows, with a lot of songs.
What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we have never been there, we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to do the best show possible, with a wide variety of songs; we will try to interpret two songs from each album and offer our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What's the reason for that?
I think it’s partly because we have nine records and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, that’s why it’s very hard to choose which songs to play each night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven’t played in a very long time, it helps us stay focused and surprises us because it reminds us of why we loved those songs and that we may have forgotten.
It makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it becomes more interesting for people as well.
With this tour, you celebrate 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve accomplished?
Yes, absolutely.
“First of all, I don’t think any of us imagined that we were going to form a big rock band, and the fact that we’ve been doing it for over 20 years makes it feel like a dream.
We continue to tell our blessings and the fact that we can continue to make music together excites us a lot.
We love each other and we love making music.
We are lucky to go to places in the world that we have always wanted to go to.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What does it mean for you to have been a fundamental element in the creation of grunge?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group of great groups.
We are very friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is uncommon.
From time to time, a group emerges from a city, but it is much stranger when five or ten groups leave the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we participated in a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we are lucky to be still friends with all of them and it is an honor for us to be part of this Seattle sound that has emerged.
It is also very strange that a group like yours stays together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only this is much longer than many bands normally last.
Firstly, I believe that we are all lucky to be alive, and secondly, we all care about others.
We are all close friends and thanks to this there are musical boulevards that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We have confidence in each other with everyone’s music and it couldn’t be better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity has not been easy; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do what you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we grew up, it was easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure we don’t spend too much time on tour because it’s easy to fall into this game of great crowds and people who love your music.
If we do not forget that people are there for music, it helps us not to forget that we must respect the music and what brought it, not to mention the fact that we are famous and a rock star, which does not really interest any of us.
How do you remember your other project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote good songs and in the beginning it was great.
We were a band for almost three years and we didn't release a record until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There was a lot of frustration for the fact that it lasted so little and the most important is the fact that we are still very close friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who started in the band with us and when I listen to a song or I see a picture I think of the amazing person that Andy was, and how fun it was to work with, and how fun it was to laugh at all.
He was an amazing human being and we miss him.
The national group Las Robertas will open the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder and for that you chose her for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos with different proposals and that was the group we liked the most, so we are looking forward to seeing what Las Robertas can offer live and it must be very distracting.
Why do you always change the lyrics of Yello Ledbetter live?
This is a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don’t know.
He sings it and I think he does it with the first words he imagines.
As a bass player, what are his influences?
There are so many...
Among the first ones I remember are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many influences, I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I love.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge relevant despite the fact that it is no longer fashionable?
I think we all feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I just mentioned, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the ones that came out at the same time and, if it’s relevant now, I think it’s wonderful because it’s a music that’s worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are now making the best music ever.
At first, his music had more obscure content and now it has become more positive.
What is the reason for this change?
It’s interesting, because I think there are songs in the new album that seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe, that qualify as very dark songs, even though these may sound a little positive.
With both, when Ed played them for me, I cried when I listened to them and these are deep dark songs.
I think if you grow up and there’s trauma in your life and you lose a parent or friend, those things start to influence your art and your music and those songs probably represent that to me.
I also think we can be happy and even that way we can make dark music.
