Fujimori Hospitalized Again for Medical Examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was hospitalized Tuesday in a public hospital to be evaluated for muscle strength loss that he has in his feet, his family doctor said.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year sentence for human rights violations committed during his government (1990-2000) suffers from various ailments, including a tongue cancer for which he has been operated four times and is under control.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga, his personal physician, told Canal N television that Fujimori will be evaluated for three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the reason for the pain and loss of strength in its lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori would be a candidate to get the benefit of the remission of the sentence for humanitarian reasons, no doubt, he said that he does not want it because he feels innocent.
He has been operated on four times of tongue cancer, he has a weight loss of 18 kilograms, and other pathologies, such as severe erosive gastritis, a pancreas cyst, kidney stones, high blood pressure and circulation problems in the feet, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been serving time in the National Police Special Operations Directorate since September 2007.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the death of 25 people because of an army annihilation squadron that operated clandestinely during the early years of his government.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official procession, headed by Uruguayan President José Mujica, and made up of various ministers and bosses, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday to expand trade between the two nations and address political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with its Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n, the high point of a long agenda of meetings with political, commercial authorities and a meeting with the community of Uruguayan residents in Mexico, according to the agenda released by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara will be “proper for the exchange of information in political affairs between the two nations,” according to information published by the South American country’s presidency on its website.
According to local media, Mujica is trying to convince Calder<0xC3><0xB3>n to support Uruguay in the incident with France that took place when French President Nicolas Sarkozy included the South American country on the list of tax havens, in the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community countries that continue to be tax havens, a statement that provoked the rejection of Uruguay and the call for consultations of its ambassador from this European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group of the world’s strongest emerging and developed countries, and has been in force with the South American country since January this year, a convention to exchange tax information to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has tried in recent years to speed up the implementation of tax-exchange agreements to get out of the "grey list" of the Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD), integrated by countries that do not implement all international standards of cooperation in tax matters.
At the commercial level, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in force since 2004, which has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations.
