Secretary Dionisio Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come gives details of the air crash in which the Secretary of the Government, Francisco Blake and seven other people lost their lives
The Secretariat for Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results highlighted on the accident in which the Secretary of Government, Francisco Blake Mora and seven other people lost their lives, indicate that the helicopter crashed directly into the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before taking off the aircraft, the pilot found that the weather conditions were adequate to fly.
"The elements that seem to indicate that the unit had various contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with the trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage."
He also informed that the unit was designed for 19 people, so the unit met the requirements for transporting personnel.
In addition, he said that the investigations done in the impact area do not report the appearance of parts on the ground.
"In a search it was reported that there are no parts or components of the aircraft in another location, the impact was presented in a structural way.
“The helicopter was designed for 19 passengers and met the requirements to carry them.
The ground had a slope of seven to 30 degrees of inclination.
For now, the secretary has assured that a priority is to have the results as soon as possible; but the investigation can last a few months, it can even last a year.
In turn, Gilberto L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services, assured that at the time of the impact, the helicopter of the Presidential Major State was operating at cruising speed and this happened on a soft ground ascending.
"This information supports the hypothesis of normal cruiser operation at the time of impact," he says.
During the press conference, the holder of the TBS, Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come, listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to the aeronautical regulations, the flight was carried out according to the visual flight rules, which implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
Reports in the AICM mentioned adequate conditions for takeoff, and as the aircraft advanced towards the border area between DF and the State of Mexico there were layers of low-altitude cloudiness.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to cloud conditions the crew sought a lower altitude area and greater visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of the impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last record of the aircraft on the radar coincide, probably before the impact there was neither loss of control nor alteration of the flight path.
Dispersion of the remains of the aircraft in a reduced area:
The information available so far suggests that the impact occurred on a straight and lateral trajectory.
The model of dispersion of the remains of the aircraft makes it possible to assume that the helicopter collided with the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No traces of fire or explosion have been detected:
In the place of the accident there is still no trace in the remains of the aircraft of a type of explosion or fire.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that the aircraft had multiple contacts with the ground.
During the field work, parts of the aircraft were found at a height of 9 thousand 200 feet above average sea level, the ground had a slope that goes from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which he may have disarticulated along his journey.
The information provides elements that appear to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts with the ground.
After careful research in a wider area than the surrounding area, no scattered parts of the aircraft were found around the accident, which supports the presumption that the impact occurred under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find Obesity Gene
Social Insurance leads an investigation to discover the obesity gene in the case of children and young people; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the obesity gene in the case of children and young people, called the 'Genetics of Obesity in Children and Adolescents' protocol that will allow to have the markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, Miguel Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry at the Hospital des Specialités of the National Medical Centre of the 20th Century, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The investigation invites the eligible or non-eligible population to attend the IMSS participating sports units in Valle de México, where the evidence is given to minors every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He pointed out that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from October 8, the activity takes place in the Nezahualc<0xC3><0xB3>yolt Sports Unit (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the goal of gathering 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Independencia Sports Unit (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of Distrito Federal).
