Energy policy:
The facts must prevail over the dogmas.
If it is a subject that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or under the influence of emotion, it is indeed energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affects the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is healthy that an electoral meeting should be an opportunity to reflect on such issues and on the place where nuclear power is located.
The debate will only be fruitful if it explores the full economic, social and environmental implications of the options proposed.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
While we are 7 billion human beings on the planet, demographic change will lead to a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, unless we deprive a huge part of the world’s population of a vital element.
At the same time, it will be necessary to alleviate the scarcity of fossil resources in order to continue to produce electricity permanently, not to mention the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, a missing topic in the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident did not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to give up nuclear power.
This is not the case for Belgium, which is subject to the need to be able to find an alternative source capable of replacing itself, nor for Switzerland, which just intends to build only state-of-the-art power plants.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name but a few, are pursuing their projects with determination.
The United States, after Fukushima, decided to add a unit to their fleet by resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, which focuses on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, reality contradicts discourse.
The choice of Berlin will result in an increase in the price of electricity, an energy dependence aggravated by the increased use of imported gas, in particular from Russia, a jump in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of gas and coal-fired power plants.
In a few months, all of these bad effects are already being felt.
The case of Denmark is to be considered.
European champion of wind power, of which it draws 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittent wind; according to which its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the constancy of our energy policy, our neighbors pay a 40% higher electricity bill than that of French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key factor of competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of the industrial tool on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear power would lead to a sharp increase in the price of electricity, which would make illusory the beautiful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power.
A price that a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially since they do not manifest a fundamental opposition to this energy, the polls show it.
Recall that the energy policy of our country has allowed to build an industrial sector of 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 induced jobs.
Strongly exporting, it leads a galaxy of SMEs specialized in international markets and makes them highly creative of non-delocalizable jobs.
If France were to decide to leave nuclear power, it would sacrifice many of these SMEs by reducing the 6 billion euros of French exports of nuclear equipment and services annually.
Which electrician would command an EPR designed to run for sixty years while its manufacturer’s decline would be programmed?
To solve the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no source of production of miracle electricity, no more than there is a diabolical one.
Areva’s development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear power, maintaining the highest level of safety is an absolute imperative.
In France, we have a Safety Authority that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing plants as well as the Flamanville site.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited by the same obsession with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
