Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy carried out under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - the collection of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of the figure, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "country of human rights" of France.
More recently, it was the administrative harassment of foreign students that made the news, the Minister of the Interior (read Liberation of May 23) proclaiming at the passage that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and restaurant servers".
But it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
There is a fairly broad consensus between the left and the right on this issue.
On the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed people should not be a problem in a country comprising nearly 2 million immigrant workers", and on the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot welcome all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared left and right.
For both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that will be shown to immigrants.
In his program, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Hollande speaks out against banalities, indicating that co-development will solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be paying electorally; but it is economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in a recent book synthesizing the most recent economic knowledge about immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among experts on the impact of migration on the global economy.
Restricting immigration anemic growth and harm to employment.
Fears about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they risk substituting for national workers, particularly the low-skilled, who are putting downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, mostly practicing trades in sectors with a lack of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract domestic workers, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors in which training does not follow job offers.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon will have difficulty working in a country with a shortage of anesthesiologists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants mean that the arrivals of immigrants have a positive effect on the salaries and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri calculated that an increase of 1% in migration flows results in an increase of 0.6 to 0.9% in real long-term wages.
And this does not take into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (strong proportion of naturalized immigrants among the American Nobel Prizes; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, averaging 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany, an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (revenues minus expenses) of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>150,000 to public budgets on average over the course of his or her life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of his term, to look for the missing growth points "with teeth".
The teeth in question, used to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it remains to think of European democracy
Democracy is a precious good; it is also a fragile good.
The European continent should be able to remember him who, for having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, experienced throughout the twentieth century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that it would be enough for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, to exercise the vote, and to exercise it in the most direct way possible.
We know, since Napoleon "the Little", that it was an ease of thought.
Universal suffrage, to be the necessary condition of democracy, is not the sufficient condition and can even become an “instrument of oppression” as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public mind, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, the Enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis in Europe we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is also and above all a crisis of politics and democracy.
The palinody of the true Greek referendum has had in this regard the value of a double revelator: that of the need for a powerful return to politics, but also that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic struggle have shifted today, and for many of them, Republican soldiers are no longer shooting in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain from demanding a succession of national referendums, organized according to needs and in a dispersed order.
A white-singing to the absolute European monarch or a united leap in the emptiness of the nationalist retreat: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want cuts but a common, full-fledged, serene and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, in Italy, in Spain, in Portugal - we can no longer stop the enumeration - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that bends to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, which suffers from its impotence and its lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is humiliated on the international stage.
We are concerned about transfers of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe that is slowly losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The urgency is to give back to popular sovereignty the leadership of the European project.
Because it is together, that Europeans will be able to reduce the weight of their debts, free themselves from markets and prepare for the future by investing.
The way out of the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, except of course to lead us to disaster.
After fighting for a long time this proposal of the socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone today calls for the European economic government.
Let's go.
But to think of it without a stronger political and democratic integration, and lived as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and a new deadlock.
We must take on a new stage of European construction.
To make the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" republicans.
The revolution in the interests could not be enough.
This lesson remains valid.
We must build a more integrated Europe economically.
This can only be achieved by building a more democratic Europe politically, a genuine European people's sovereignty.
To make Europe, let's make Europeans.
