Nord Stream, the new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream pipeline, which connects Western Europe directly to Russia via the bottom of the Baltic Sea, entered service.
It must supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million homes.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with brilliance.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part in the opening of the Nord Stream, a new gas pipeline that directly connects Russia to Germany under the sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte turned together the steering wheel of the valve commanding the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe through a first 1,224 km tube connecting the St. Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second tube must be completed by the end of 2012, allowing a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas to be delivered, which is the equivalent of all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third on the same track.
For Gazprom, the completion on time and in time of this huge construction site looks like a victory.
The project had been strongly challenged by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The Nord Stream will be able to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries lose some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream to a "new Germano-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, in supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies.
But it is at the cost of a weakening of Europe's energy, since the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has succeeded in winning its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavily gas consumers, and whose deposits are in decline.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically," Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of this gas pipeline, demonstrating how big gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the wide smiles displayed by the leaders of Gazprom, present in numbers in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater tube is made of concrete sheathed steel to protect it from ship anchors.
It lies at the bottom of the sea, at 200 m on average.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to the Second World War.
“A hundred had to be removed or destroyed, by precaution,” said Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to multiply the measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, as heavy as 242 Eiffel Towers, which nothing interrupts over its entire length: neither valve, nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project leaders gave up on it while the Swedes were reluctant to see a Russian state corporation settle permanently off their coasts.
“In the event of a breakdown, we stop the passage of the gas in less than a minute,” says Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller.
In case of leakage, the gas contained in the gas pipeline therefore escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who have planned the welds to experience a leak every 100,000 years.
Monitoring of the state of the pipeline is ensured by a submarine robot, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an apparatus that circulates inside the pipeline.
In the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, wide by a meter in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
On arrival, after three full days of travel at the speed of 3 meters per second, it delivers accurate information on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to run for fifty years without having to undergo any repair.
The flow of gas is simply ensured by pressure.
It is 200 bars at the start, and 100 on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Germany’s E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), the Netherlands’ Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each) joined.
These five companies created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased this company, for twenty renewable years, the total capacity for gas transportation.
“Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported,” says Jens M<0xC3><0xBC>ller.
The financing of the construction of the gas pipeline was provided to 30% by the shareholders and to 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works is expected to reach 7.4 billion euros for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are safe to bear their costs, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that arrives, before it is transferred into German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a brand name.
