A success that made enviable: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate of people with disabilities so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th week for the employment of disabled people opens today.
Despite a voluntary public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate of people with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared to 9% for the entire population.
Disheartening?
“No,” points out <0xC3><0x89>ric Blanchet, general manager of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of disabled people.
“The progress made over the past 15 years is significant.”
“At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher.”
“However, there is still a lot to be done.”
It must be said that for the unemployed with disabilities, there are still many obstacles to accessing employment.
They are rather old: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the baccalaureate and out of the 2.3 million higher education students, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for people with disabilities, compared to an average of 38%.
In short, so many criteria that make returning to work singularly difficult, and that "constitute the knot of the problem," according to Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
This is for objective brakes.
It remains the unsaid, the mentality that evolves, of course, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité indicated that the managers interviewed had "a low level of knowledge of the disability", with "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, people with mental or intellectual disabilities".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set in a law of... 1987.
The last known figures, which date back to 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the organization responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with the law.
The proof: the number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created a strong pressure on companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also translates into a real awareness, especially in large groups.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
